{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610914"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16181"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16181"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.14,0.19,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66005"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66005"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHuman breast milk contains diverse microbial communities that contribute to infant health and development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria is most commonly found in healthy human breast milk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcus epidermidis","Escherichia coli","Clostridium difficile","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Mycobacterium tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHuman breast milk is not sterile and contains a complex microbiota that contributes to the health and development of the infant\u0027s gut and immune system. \u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus epidermidis\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most commonly found bacteria in healthy breast milk and plays a beneficial role by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHelping to protect the infant from pathogenic bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContributing to the development of the infant\u0027s microbiome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent organisms that are not typically found in healthy breast milk:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly found in the intestinal tract and can indicate contamination if present in breast milk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridium difficile\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily an intestinal pathogen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E is an opportunistic pathogen that may cause mastitis but is not part of normal breast milk flora\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E can rarely be transmitted through breast milk in active tuberculosis but is not part of normal flora\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther beneficial bacteria commonly found in breast milk include \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species and \u003Cem\u003ELactobacillus\u003C/em\u003E species, which contribute to infant immune system development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Human breast milk contains beneficial bacteria including Staphylococcus, Streptococcus, and Lactobacillus species that contribute to infant gut microbiome development.","The normal breast milk microbiome helps protect against mastitis and supports infant immune system development."],"references":["Ballard O, Morrow AL. Human milk composition: nutrients and bioactive factors. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2013 Feb;60(1):49-74. doi: 10.1016/j.pcl.2012.10.002. PMID: 23178060; PMCID: PMC3586783","Kim SY, Yi DY. Components of human breast milk: from macronutrient to microbiome and microRNA. Clin Exp Pediatr. 2020 Aug;63(8):301-309. doi: 10.3345/cep.2020.00059. Epub 2020 Mar 23. PMID: 32252145; PMCID: PMC7402982","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Biswas SK, Banerjee S, Baker GW, Kuo CY, Chowdhury I. The Mammary Gland: Basic Structure and Molecular Signaling during Development. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Mar 31;23(7):3883. doi: 10.3390/ijms23073883. PMID: 35409243; PMCID: PMC8998991","Rio-Aige K, Azagra-Boronat I, Castell M, Selma-Royo M, Collado MC, Rodr\u00edguez-Lagunas MJ, P\u00e9rez-Cano FJ. The Breast Milk Immunoglobulinome. Nutrients. 2021 May 26;13(6):1810. doi: 10.3390/nu13061810. PMID: 34073540; PMCID: PMC8230140"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16181"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51455"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T17:35:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T17:35:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8872"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66005"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https:/